---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="About the Simulation Learning System.">
  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>About</span>
  </div>

  <h1>About the Simulation Learning System</h1>
  <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: 2.5rem; font-size: 1.1rem;">
    A clinical education platform designed to advance healthcare provider competency through
    high-fidelity simulation experiences.
  </p>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Our Mission</h2>
    <p>
      The Simulation Learning System exists to bridge the gap between theoretical knowledge and
      real-world clinical performance. By immersing learners in realistic, high-stakes patient
      scenarios, we foster the development of critical thinking, clinical judgment, and
      interprofessional teamwork skills that save lives.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our cases are built upon current evidence-based guidelines, peer-reviewed literature,
      and best practices from leading medical and nursing education bodies.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>How Cases Are Structured</h2>
    <p>Every case in the Simulation Learning System follows a consistent structure:</p>
    <ul class="objective-list">
      <li><strong>Case Overview</strong> — Patient story and clinical scenario context</li>
      <li><strong>Patient Information</strong> — Demographics, medical history, medications, allergies</li>
      <li><strong>Initial Vital Signs</strong> — Baseline patient state with abnormalities to identify</li>
      <li><strong>Learning Objectives</strong> — Specific, measurable clinical competency goals</li>
      <li><strong>Scenario Progression</strong> — Phased timeline of events and expected interventions</li>
      <li><strong>Debriefing Guide</strong> — Facilitated reflection questions for post-simulation discussion</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Difficulty Levels</h2>
    <div class="card-grid" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
      <div class="card">
        <h3>🟢 Beginner</h3>
        <p>
          Designed for early learners or orientation settings. Cases focus on recognition of
          common conditions and application of straightforward clinical protocols.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>🟡 Intermediate</h3>
        <p>
          Suitable for learners with foundational clinical knowledge. Cases introduce complexity
          through comorbidities, time pressure, and team communication challenges.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>🔴 Advanced</h3>
        <p>
          For experienced clinicians and inter-professional teams. Cases feature multi-system
          involvement, competing priorities, ethical dilemmas, and rapid deterioration.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Target Learners</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Medical students and residents</li>
      <li>Nursing students and registered nurses</li>
      <li>Paramedics and EMS providers</li>
      <li>Respiratory therapists</li>
      <li>Advanced practice providers (NPs, PAs)</li>
      <li>Inter-professional healthcare teams</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Curriculum Alignment</h2>
    <p>
      Cases within the Simulation Learning System are aligned with widely recognized educational
      standards and clinical guidelines, including:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>ACLS / BLS / PALS (American Heart Association)</li>
      <li>ATLS (American College of Surgeons)</li>
      <li>Surviving Sepsis Campaign Guidelines</li>
      <li>ASA and ACC/AHA Clinical Practice Guidelines</li>
      <li>INACSL Standards of Best Practice: Simulation℠</li>
      <li>NLN Jeffries Simulation Theory</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Using This Repository</h2>
    <p>
      Each case page contains everything a simulation facilitator needs to run a complete
      educational scenario. Facilitators are encouraged to:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Review the learning objectives before the session</li>
      <li>Adapt the scenario progression to learner level and institutional context</li>
      <li>Use the debriefing guide to structure the post-simulation reflection</li>
      <li>Supplement with moulage, standardized patients, or high-fidelity mannequins as appropriate</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
